</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F6B8652FEE55FF816B8DD1A5FECFF10C" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="BE1D36A4EE55FF816B8DD1A5FDFCF2CD" blockId="19.[151,1436,151,603]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="8CD6EAB6EE55FF816B8DD1A5FEA2F3A8" bold="true" box="[198,330,229,255]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Discussion</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName id="79A24D27EE55FF816A24D1A5FD2AF3A9" box="[367,706,229,254]" class="Liliopsida" family="Marantaceae" genus="Monotagma" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zingiberales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aurantispathum">
<emphasis id="8CD6EAB6EE55FF816A24D1A5FD2AF3A9" box="[367,706,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Monotagma aurantispathum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily recognized by having orange bracts which are ± imbricate throughout anthesis. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="79A24D27EE55FF8169E6D04CFC9DF272" box="[685,885,268,293]" class="Liliopsida" family="Marantaceae" genus="Monotagma" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zingiberales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="smaragdinum">
<emphasis id="8CD6EAB6EE55FF8169E6D04CFC9DF272" box="[685,885,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">M. smaragdinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="79A24D27EE55FF8168E5D04CFBB6F272" box="[942,1118,268,293]" class="Liliopsida" family="Marantaceae" genus="Monotagma" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zingiberales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="flavicomum">
<emphasis id="8CD6EAB6EE55FF8168E5D04CFBB6F272" box="[942,1118,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">M. flavicomum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both of which have bracts spreading throughout anthesis. It differs from both by having outer staminodes that are smaller (1–3 × 0.5–1 vs. 5.5–7 × 
<quantity id="795A9B41EE55FF816A63D019FE54F224" box="[296,444,345,371]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="2.5">2.5–5.5 mm</quantity>
) and narrowly elliptic (vs. spathulate) with entire apex (vs. bilobed), and shorter capsules (10–12 vs. 
<quantity id="795A9B41EE55FF816ACFD0C0FDEFF2CD" box="[388,519,384,410]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="2.1" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="18.5" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="16.0">16–21 mm</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
